<doc id="40326" wikidata="Q77601250" url="?curid=40326" title="Definite matrix">
<text>In mathematics, a symmetric matrix formula_1 with real entries is positive-definite if the real number formula_2 is positive for every nonzero real column vector formula_3 where formula_4 is the row vector transpose of formula_5
More generally, a Hermitian matrix (that is, a complex matrix equal to its conjugate transpose) is positive-definite if the real number formula_6 is positive for every nonzero complex column vector formula_7 where formula_8 denotes the conjugate transpose of formula_9

Positive semi-definite matrices are defined similarly, except that the scalars formula_2 and formula_6 are required to be positive &quot;or zero&quot; (that is, nonnegative). Negative-definite and negative semi-definite matrices are defined analogously. A matrix that is not positive semi-definite and not negative semi-definite is sometimes called &quot;indefinite&quot;.

Some authors use more general definitions of definiteness, permitting the matrices to be non-symmetric or non-Hermitian. The properties of these generalized definite matrices are explored in the section #Extension for non-Hermitian square matrices below, but are not the main focus of this article.

== Ramifications ==
It follows from the above definitions that a matrix is positive-definite if and only if it is the matrix of a positive-definite quadratic form or Hermitian form. In other words, a matrix is positive-definite if and only if it defines an inner product.

Positive-definite and positive-semidefinite matrices can be characterized in many ways, which may explain the importance of the concept in various parts of mathematics. A matrix is positive-definite if and only if it satisfies any of the following equivalent conditions.
* formula_1 is congruent with a diagonal matrix with positive real entries. 
* formula_1 is symmetric or Hermitian, and all its eigenvalues are real and positive.
* formula_1 is symmetric or Hermitian, and all its leading principal minors are positive.
* There exists an invertible matrix formula_15 with conjugate transpose formula_16 such that formula_17
A matrix is positive semi-definite if it satisfies similar equivalent conditions where &quot;positive&quot; is replaced by &quot;nonnegative&quot;, &quot;invertible matrix&quot; is replaced by &quot;matrix&quot;, and the word &quot;leading&quot; is removed.

Positive-definite and positive-semidefinite real matrices are at the basis of convex optimization, since, given a function of several real variables that is twice differentiable, then if its Hessian matrix (matrix of its second partial derivatives) is positive-definite at a point formula_18 then the function is convex near , and, conversely, if the function is convex near formula_18 then the Hessian matrix is positive-semidefinite at formula_20

The set of positive definite matrices is an open convex cone, while the set of positive semi-definite matrices is a closed convex cone.

== Definitions ==
In the following definitions, formula_4 is the transpose of formula_3 formula_8 is the conjugate transpose of formula_7 and formula_25 denotes the zero-vector.

=== Definitions for real matrices ===
An formula_26 symmetric real matrix formula_1 is said to be positive-definite if formula_28 for all non-zero formula_29 in formula_30 Formally,

An formula_26 symmetric real matrix formula_1 is said to be positive-semidefinite or non-negative-definite if formula_33 for all formula_29 in formula_35 Formally,

An formula_26 symmetric real matrix formula_1 is said to be negative-definite if formula_38 for all non-zero formula_29 in formula_40 Formally,

An formula_26 symmetric real matrix formula_1 is said to be negative-semidefinite or non-positive-definite if formula_43 for all formula_29 in formula_35 Formally,

An formula_26 symmetric real matrix which is neither positive semidefinite nor negative semidefinite is called indefinite.

=== Definitions for complex matrices ===
The following definitions all involve the term formula_47 Notice that this is always a real number for any Hermitian square matrix formula_48

An formula_26 Hermitian complex matrix formula_1 is said to be positive-definite if formula_51 for all non-zero formula_52 in formula_53 Formally,

An formula_26 Hermitian complex matrix formula_1 is said to be positive semi-definite or non-negative-definite if formula_56 for all formula_52 in formula_53 Formally,

An formula_26 Hermitian complex matrix formula_1 is said to be negative-definite if formula_61 for all non-zero formula_52 in formula_53 Formally,

An formula_26 Hermitian complex matrix formula_1 is said to be negative semi-definite or non-positive-definite if formula_66 for all formula_52 in formula_53 Formally,

An formula_26 Hermitian complex matrix which is neither positive semidefinite nor negative semidefinite is called indefinite.

=== Consistency between real and complex definitions ===
Since every real matrix is also a complex matrix, the definitions of &quot;definiteness&quot; for the two classes must agree.

For complex matrices, the most common definition says that formula_1 is positive-definite if and only if formula_71 is real and positive for every non-zero complex column vectors formula_72 This condition implies that formula_1 is Hermitian (i.e. its transpose is equal to its conjugate), since formula_71 being real, it equals its conjugate transpose formula_75 for every formula_7 which implies formula_77 

By this definition, a positive-definite &quot;real&quot; matrix formula_1 is Hermitian, hence symmetric; and formula_79 is positive for all non-zero &quot;real&quot; column vectors formula_72 However the last condition alone is not sufficient for formula_1 to be positive-definite. For example, if
formula_82

then for any real vector formula_52 with entries formula_84 and formula_85 we have formula_86 which is always positive if formula_52 is not zero. However, if formula_52 is the complex vector with entries and formula_89 one gets

formula_90

which is not real. Therefore, formula_1 is not positive-definite.

On the other hand, for a &quot;symmetric&quot; real matrix formula_92 the condition &quot;formula_93 for all nonzero real vectors formula_52&quot; &quot;does&quot; imply that formula_1 is positive-definite in the complex sense.

===Notation===
If a Hermitian matrix formula_1 is positive semi-definite, one sometimes writes formula_97 and if formula_1 is positive-definite one writes formula_99 To denote that formula_1 is negative semi-definite one writes formula_101 and to denote that formula_1 is negative-definite one writes formula_103

The notion comes from functional analysis where positive semidefinite matrices define positive operators. If two matrices formula_104 and formula_15 satisfy formula_106 we can define a non-strict partial order formula_107 that is reflexive, antisymmetric, and transitive; It is not a total order, however, as formula_108 in general, may be indefinite.

A common alternative notation is formula_109 formula_110 formula_111 and formula_112 for positive semi-definite and positive-definite, negative semi-definite and negative-definite matrices, respectively. This may be confusing, as sometimes nonnegative matrices (respectively, nonpositive matrices) are also denoted in this way.

== Examples ==
== Eigenvalues ==
Let formula_1 be an formula_26 Hermitian matrix (this includes real symmetric matrices). All eigenvalues of formula_1 are real, and their sign characterize its definiteness:
* formula_1 is positive definite if and only if all of its eigenvalues are positive.
* formula_1 is positive semi-definite if and only if all of its eigenvalues are non-negative.
* formula_1 is negative definite if and only if all of its eigenvalues are negative.
* formula_1 is negative semi-definite if and only if all of its eigenvalues are non-positive.
* formula_1 is indefinite if and only if it has both positive and negative eigenvalues.

Let formula_121 be an eigendecomposition of formula_92 where formula_123 is a unitary complex matrix whose columns comprise an orthonormal basis of eigenvectors of formula_92 and formula_125 is a &quot;real&quot; diagonal matrix whose main diagonal contains the corresponding eigenvalues. The matrix formula_1 may be regarded as a diagonal matrix formula_125 that has been re-expressed in coordinates of the (eigenvectors) basis formula_128 Put differently, applying formula_1 to some vector formula_7 giving formula_131 is the same as changing the basis to the eigenvector coordinate system using formula_132 giving formula_133 applying the stretching transformation formula_125 to the result, giving formula_135 and then changing the basis back using formula_136 giving formula_137

With this in mind, the one-to-one change of variable formula_138 shows that formula_71 is real and positive for any complex vector formula_52 if and only if formula_141 is real and positive for any formula_142 in other words, if formula_125 is positive definite. For a diagonal matrix, this is true only if each element of the main diagonal – that is, every eigenvalue of formula_1 – is positive. Since the spectral theorem guarantees all eigenvalues of a Hermitian matrix to be real, the positivity of eigenvalues can be checked using Descartes&#x27; rule of alternating signs when the characteristic polynomial of a real, symmetric matrix formula_1 is available.

==Decomposition==

Let formula_1 be an formula_26 Hermitian matrix.
formula_1 is positive semidefinite if and only if it can be decomposed as a product
formula_149
of a matrix formula_15 with its conjugate transpose.

When formula_1 is real, formula_15 can be real as well and the decomposition can be written as formula_153

formula_1 is positive definite if and only if such a decomposition exists with formula_15 invertible.
More generally, formula_1 is positive semidefinite with rank formula_157 if and only if a decomposition exists with a formula_158 matrix formula_15 of full row rank (i.e. of rank formula_157).
Moreover, for any decomposition formula_161 formula_162

&lt;/math&gt; as the diagonal matrix whose entries are non-negative square roots of eigenvalues.
Then formula_163 for formula_164
If moreover formula_1 is positive definite, then the eigenvalues are (strictly) positive, so formula_166 is invertible, and hence formula_167 is invertible as well.
If formula_1 has rank formula_169 then it has exactly formula_157 positive eigenvalues and the others are zero, hence in formula_167 all but formula_157 rows are all zeroed.
Cutting the zero rows gives a formula_158 matrix formula_174 such that formula_175

The columns formula_176 of formula_15 can be seen as vectors in the complex or real vector space formula_178 respectively.
Then the entries of formula_1 are inner products (that is dot products, in the real case) of these vectors
formula_180
In other words, a Hermitian matrix formula_1 is positive semidefinite if and only if it is the Gram matrix of some vectors formula_182
It is positive definite if and only if it is the Gram matrix of some linearly independent vectors.
In general, the rank of the Gram matrix of vectors formula_176 equals the dimension of the space spanned by these vectors.

===Uniqueness up to unitary transformations===
The decomposition is not unique: 
if formula_184 for some formula_158 matrix formula_15 and if formula_187 is any unitary formula_188 matrix (meaning formula_189),
then formula_190 for formula_191

However, this is the only way in which two decompositions can differ: The decomposition is unique up to unitary transformations.
More formally, if formula_104 is a formula_158 matrix and formula_15 is a formula_195 matrix such that formula_196
then there is a formula_197 matrix formula_187 with orthonormal columns (meaning formula_199) such that formula_200
When formula_201 this means formula_187 is unitary.

This statement has an intuitive geometric interpretation in the real case:
let the columns of formula_104 and formula_15 be the vectors formula_205 and formula_176 in formula_207
A real unitary matrix is an orthogonal matrix, which describes a rigid transformation (an isometry of Euclidean space formula_208) preserving the 0 point (i.e. rotations and reflections, without translations). 
Therefore, the dot products formula_209 and formula_210 are equal if and only if some rigid transformation of formula_208 transforms the vectors formula_205 to formula_213 (and 0 to 0).

===Square root===

A Hermitian matrix formula_1 is positive semidefinite if and only if there is a positive semidefinite matrix formula_15 (in particular formula_15 is Hermitian, so formula_217) satisfying formula_218 This matrix formula_15 is unique, is called the &quot;non-negative square root&quot; of formula_92 and is denoted with formula_221
When formula_1 is positive definite, so is formula_223 hence it is also called the &quot;positive square root&quot; of formula_48

The non-negative square root should not be confused with other decompositions formula_225
