* If formula_257 then formula_263 for all formula_264 if and only if formula_265 So, since the polar dual of an ellipsoid is also an ellipsoid with the same principal axes, with inverse lengths, we have formula_266 That is, if formula_267 is positive-definite, then formula_268 for all formula_269 if and only if formula_270
Let formula_1 be an formula_26 Hermitian matrix. The following properties are equivalent to formula_1 being positive definite:
; The associated sesquilinear form is an inner product: The sesquilinear form defined by formula_1 is the function formula_275 from formula_276 to formula_277 such that formula_278 for all formula_29 and formula_280 in formula_281 where formula_282 is the conjugate transpose of formula_283 For any complex matrix formula_92 this form is linear in formula_285 and semilinear in formula_283 Therefore, the form is an inner product on formula_277 if and only if formula_288 is real and positive for all nonzero formula_289 that is if and only if formula_1 is positive definite. (In fact, every inner product on formula_277 arises in this fashion from a Hermitian positive definite matrix.)
; Its leading principal minors are all positive: The th leading principal minor of a matrix formula_1 is the determinant of its upper-left formula_188 sub-matrix. It turns out that a matrix is positive definite if and only if all these determinants are positive. This condition is known as Sylvester&#x27;s criterion, and provides an efficient test of positive definiteness of a symmetric real matrix. Namely, the matrix is reduced to an upper triangular matrix by using elementary row operations, as in the first part of the Gaussian elimination method, taking care to preserve the sign of its determinant during pivoting process. Since the th leading principal minor of a triangular matrix is the product of its diagonal elements up to row formula_169 Sylvester&#x27;s criterion is equivalent to checking whether its diagonal elements are all positive. This condition can be checked each time a new row formula_157 of the triangular matrix is obtained.

A positive semidefinite matrix is positive definite if and only if it is invertible.
A matrix formula_1 is negative (semi)definite if and only if formula_297 is positive (semi)definite.

== Quadratic forms ==

The (purely) quadratic form associated with a real formula_26 matrix formula_1 is the function formula_300 such that formula_301 for all formula_302 formula_1 can be assumed symmetric by replacing it with formula_304 since any asymmetric part will be zeroed-out in the double-sided product.

A symmetric matrix formula_1 is positive definite if and only if its quadratic form is a strictly convex function.

More generally, any quadratic function from formula_306 to formula_307 can be written as formula_308 where formula_1 is a symmetric formula_26 matrix, formula_311 is a real and formula_312 a real constant. In the formula_313 case, this is a parabola, and just like in the formula_313 case, we have

Theorem: This quadratic function is strictly convex, and hence has a unique finite global minimum, if and only if formula_1 is positive definite.

Proof: If formula_1 is positive definite, then the function is strictly convex. Its gradient is zero at the unique point of formula_317 which must be the global minimum since the function is strictly convex. If formula_1 is not positive definite, then there exists some vector formula_319 such that formula_320 so the function formula_321 is a line or a downward parabola, thus not strictly convex and not having a global minimum.

For this reason, positive definite matrices play an important role in optimization problems.

== Simultaneous diagonalization ==
One symmetric matrix and another matrix that is both symmetric and positive definite can be simultaneously diagonalized. This is so although simultaneous diagonalization is not necessarily performed with a similarity transformation. This result does not extend to the case of three or more matrices. In this section we write for the real case. Extension to the complex case is immediate.

Let formula_1 be a symmetric and formula_267 a symmetric and positive definite matrix. Write the generalized eigenvalue equation as formula_324 where we impose that formula_29 be normalized, i.e. formula_326 Now we use Cholesky decomposition to write the inverse of formula_267 as formula_328 Multiplying by formula_187 and letting formula_330 we get formula_331 which can be rewritten as formula_332 where formula_333 Manipulation now yields formula_334 where formula_335 is a matrix having as columns the generalized eigenvectors and formula_336 is a diagonal matrix of the generalized eigenvalues. Now premultiplication with formula_337 gives the final result: formula_338 and formula_339 but note that this is no longer an orthogonal diagonalization with respect to the inner product where formula_333 In fact, we diagonalized formula_1 with respect to the inner product induced by formula_342

Note that this result does not contradict what is said on simultaneous diagonalization in the article Diagonalizable matrix, which refers to simultaneous diagonalization by a similarity transformation. Our result here is more akin to a simultaneous diagonalization of two quadratic forms, and is useful for optimization of one form under conditions on the other.

